04877nam a22009615i 9780814768402DE-B159720200723103303.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||200723t20112011nyu    fo  d z      eng d  a97808147684027 a10.18574/97808147684022doi  a(DE-B1597)547984  a(OCoLC)708566403  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anyucUS-NY 4aE184.A1bP42 2011eb 7aSOC0310002bisacsh04a305.8009732221 aPerry, Imani, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aMore Beautiful and More Terrible :bThe Embrace and Transcendence of Racial Inequality in the United States /cImani Perry. 1aNew York, NY : bNew York University Press, c[2011] 4cÂ©2011  a1 online resource  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tAcknowledgments -- tPreface -- tIntroduction -- t1. "It Wasn't Me!" -- t2. It's All of Us -- t3. Telling Tales Out of School -- t4. The House That Jack Built -- t5. "I Always Feel Like Somebody's Watchin' Me" -- t6. Exceptionally Yours -- t7. Black Taxes and White Wages -- tConclusion -- tNotes -- tIndex -- tAbout the Author 0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aFor a nation that often optimistically claims to be post-racial, we are still mired in the practices of racial inequality that plays out in law, policy, and in our local communities. One of two explanations is often given for this persistent phenomenon: On the one hand, we might be hypocritical-saying one thing, and doing or believing another; on the other, it might have little to do with us individually but rather be inherent to the structure of American society.More Beautiful and More Terrible compels us to think beyond this insufficient dichotomy in order to see how racial inequality is perpetuated. Imani Perry asserts that the U.S. is in a new and distinct phase of racism that is "post-intentional": neither based on the intentional discrimination of the past, nor drawing upon biological concepts of race. Drawing upon the insights and tools of critical race theory, social policy, law, sociology and cultural studies, she demonstrates how post-intentional racism works and maintains that it cannot be addressed solely through the kinds of structural solutions of the Left or the values arguments of the Right. Rather, the author identifies a place in the middle-a space of "righteous hope"-and articulates a notion of ethics and human agency that will allow us to expand and amplify that hope.To paraphrase James Baldwin, when talking about race, it is both more terrible than most think, but also more beautiful than most can imagine, with limitless and open-ended possibility. Perry leads readers down the path of imagining the possible and points to the way forward.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 23. Jul 2020) 0aRacismzUnited States. 4aCompelling. 4aPerry. 4aUS. 4aasserts. 4abased. 4abeyond. 4abiological. 4aconcepts. 4adichotomy. 4adiscrimination. 4adistinct. 4adrawing. 4ainequality. 4ainsufficient. 4aintentional. 4aneither. 4aorder. 4aperpetuated. 4aphase. 4apost-intentional. 4arace. 4aracial. 4aracism. 4athat. 4athink. 4athis. 4aupon. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Discrimination & Race Relations.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertNYUP Backlist 2000-2013z978311070644440uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780814768402423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780814768402.jpg  a978-3-11-070644-4  NYUP Backlist 2000-2013c2000d2013  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_SN  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_SN  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK